timeline.bodyText:
IMO the control flow would be better at the caller level. This method is a no-op otherwise an is just a void call from the caller. It provides some abstraction but a maintainer needs to jump around in the code to see that this is a potential no-op and when it would be a no-op. It also looks like the null check is dead-code.
I suspect some details are a bit hidden that probably could be exposed to the caller that would make the code easier to follow. For example, instead of this:
  @Override
  public Map<RetreatLocation, Collection<Unit>> splitRetreatUnits(
      final Collection<Unit> retreatUnits) {
    return Map.of(RetreatLocation.SAME_TERRITORY, retreatUnits);
  }

Perhaps the API should be:
Collection<Unit> splitRetreatUnits(
     RetreatLocation,
      final Collection<Unit> retreatUnits)

In this way it'd be more obvious that if we are calling a non-nullable method, then we'd always have a key value for 'retreatingUnits' and one would then be very comfortable removing the null check.

